&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;International women&amp;rsquo;s day was celebrated on 7 March 2020 at Gokaraju Rangaraju Institute of Engineering and Technology. International women&amp;rsquo;s day was first commemorated by the United Nations on the 8&lt;sup&gt;th &lt;/sup&gt;of March in the International women&amp;rsquo;s year 1975. The day represents an important opportunity for everyone to celebrate the contribution, progress and achievements of women, and the work towards full and equal participation of women within all areas of society.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; The lively program at G.R.I.E.T was organised by Gokaraju Rangaraju Educational society. It was volunteered by IEEE and Rythms of G.R.I.E.T. The theme behind the program was &amp;ldquo;I am generation equality: Realising women&amp;rsquo;s rights.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; The program began with a video which reflected the theme of International women&amp;rsquo;s day- &amp;ldquo;An equal world is an enabled world.&amp;rdquo; The video projected on women from different regions of the world who fought for justice, rights, gender equality and against sexual &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;harassment; followed by a video presented by the women faculty of G.R.I.E.T and Ganges valley school, who posed the sign saying &amp;ldquo; Let&amp;rsquo;s be Equal for Equal&amp;rdquo; which was drawn from Collective Individualism.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; After the presentation the Chief Administrator Sri M.G. Sekharam garu, the chief guest of the function Samantha Reddy garu, the chief guest of honour Rashmi Praveen garu, the principal of the college Dr.J. Praveen sir and Prof. Dr. Gyati Shilakari Asthana of GRCP were invited on to the dias. Then the guests and audience joined for Jyoti Prajwaalana and offered prayer to seek the divine blessings. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; The celebrations were started with a lot of enthusiasm and fanfare marking the economical, social, cultural and political achievements made by women over the years. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Prof. Dr. Gyati Shilakari Asthana addressed the gathering and spoke about the importance of celebrating women&amp;rsquo;s day and respecting the women. She highlighted that &amp;ldquo;Respect women not because of gender but because of making her own identity in the society.&amp;rdquo; This sentiment was shared by many of the event&amp;rsquo;s participants. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Dr.J. Praveen recognised the support and contribution of the women faculty in bringing accolades to the college. He cherished the puranas and said that women are known for wealth, knowledge, courage, purity and love. He also appreciated the women who supported him through his life.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Chief Administrator Sri M.G. Sekharam recalled Raja Ram Mohan Roy who first started to fight against old practices like sati sahagamanam, child marriages, dowry system and reminded us to be thankful for him. He pointed out that &amp;ldquo;Even today we have women discrimination. It is a societal problem, and it will take the entire society working together to fix it.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; The Guest of honour &lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;Smt. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;Rashmi Praveen shared how she was supported by her parents when she decided to pursue higher studies, which helped her become an independent woman&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt; and make her own identity&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Later on, the Chief guest of the function Smt. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;Samantha Reddy, who has graduated from London Business School narrated her life story and the power of Yes! She emphasised that, &amp;ldquo;Don&amp;rsquo;t be afraid to leave your comfort zone, prepare to change course and take risks.&amp;rdquo; During her brief presentation, she received piercing laudatory whistles and an enthusiastic applause of approval. She also suggested that &amp;ldquo;Self-awareness is important. Try to cultivate passion, build your network, find a purpose greater that yourself and rediscover the best in yourself.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Speaking about the accomplishments of women, Dr. Jandhyala N Murthy, Director of G.R.I.E.T stated that &amp;ldquo;stree srushti ki mulam.&amp;rdquo; He went on to underscore the importance of women in the society, noting that &amp;ldquo;Women play a key role in our society and we should support and encourage them.&amp;rdquo; He concluded his speech by saying &amp;ldquo;Vanitha lokaaniki shathakoti vandhanaalu.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Chief guests of the program were felicitated by WDC members. One of the program&amp;rsquo;s great highlights was recognizing and honouring the college&amp;rsquo;s female staff for their pivotal contribution to the college. This was followed by a wide variety of cultural program which included singing, dancing and short games with light refreshments. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Then the vote of thanks was given by the WDC convenor for the program. During the closing remarks of the program, pride and admiration of the event was expressed, commenting &amp;ldquo;the event is very successful. It is so good to see all the women faculty and students come together to celebrate such an important day. Let&amp;rsquo;s continue to work to encourage equality and move forward.&amp;rdquo; Finally, the event was concluded by singing the National Anthem.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Women are an integral part of society and face multiple challenges in every role of their life. It can be at home, office or anywhere else. Even during this struggling times of COVID -19, women are not only looking after the families but also completing their professional commitments too. It is very challenging to accomplish multiple jobs simultaneously.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To understand the concerns of women and help them overcome the stress, IEEE Women in Engineering Affinity Group, Hyderabad Section in association with IEEE Education Society is organizing a Panel Discussion with eminent personalities on &amp;ldquo;Work from home and its challenges&amp;rdquo; on 25&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt;&amp;nbsp;April 2020 from 5.00 to 6.30 PM.&lt;/p&gt;
